## Project Overview

This project implements three “crackme‑style” MIPS programs that require a correct password to continue execution. Each version increases in difficulty for an attacker trying to extract or bypass the password from the binary.

Version A: Plaintext  
 Password stored directly in .data. Very easy to recover using tools such as strings or Ghidra.

Version B: XOR‑encrypted  
 Password bytes are XOR‑encrypted and decrypted at runtime before comparison. Harder to inspect statically.

Version C: Hashed only  
 The binary contains only a 32‑bit hash. A hash of user input is compared at runtime. The real password never appears in plaintext.

## 2\. Threat Model

* The adversary can access the binary (.bin).

* The adversary can inspect symbols, strings, memory dumps, and assembly using tools such as strings, hexdump, Ghidra, and MARS memory viewer.

* The goal of the adversary is to either recover the password or bypass authentication.

* The attacker may attempt to:

  * read plaintext data (Version A)

  * recover XOR‑encrypted bytes (Version B)

  * analyze the hashing function (Version C)

  * patch branch instructions to bypass authentication

## 3\. Differences from Existing Projects

Many GitHub repositories, such as [https://github.com/ripxorip/crackmes](https://github.com/ripxorip/crackmes) and [https://github.com/QuantumWizard888/Reverse-Engineering-crackmes-with-Ghidra](https://github.com/QuantumWizard888/Reverse-Engineering-crackmes-with-Ghidra)

 feature:

* Simple XOR obfuscation examples

* Basic password-check assembly challenges

* Introductory reverse-engineering CTF tasks

Our project differs in that:

### 1\. Sequential versions

We intentionally build multiple versions with increasing difficulty, rather than providing a single challenge or challenges that don’t build off of each other.

### 2\. Full educational cycle

We cover:

* construction of binary protections

* actual adversarial evaluation

* comparison of techniques

* analysis from both attacker and defender perspectives

This structured approach is rarely done in GitHub projects.

### 3\. MIPS focus with Ghidra analysis

Most GitHub reverse engineering examples use x86 or ARM, while our project will use MIPS.

### 4\. Group exchange

Other teams will attempt to crack our programs, and we will attempt to crack theirs.  
 This reflects real security workflows rather than isolated examples such as the GitHub repo’s we found.

## 4\. Logic of Each Version

### Version A (Plaintext)

* Reads user input

* Compares with string stored in .data

### Version B (XOR‑encrypted)

* XOR‑encrypted bytes in .data

* Key is reconstructed at runtime

* Bytes decrypted before comparison

### Version C (Hashed)

* Binary stores only a 32‑bit hash

* User input hashed using custom function, then compared

## 5\. How to Run

Launch MARS, open .asm file, Assemble,  Run.

## 6\. Exporting .bin Files (for analysis)

Open MARS, Assemble the file, Hit File, Dump Memory, Choose either .text or .data depending on what you are looking for. Ensure Binary is the chosen format.

## 7\. Reverse Engineering Steps (summary)

* Version A: strings immediately reveals password

* Version B: view encrypted bytes, inspect XOR logic

* Version C: must analyze hashing logic and/or brute force
